### Prerequisite Checklist

- [X] I searched for [existing issues](https://github.com/search?q=repo%3ASFML%2FSFML&type=issues) to prevent duplicates
- [X] I searched for [existing discussions on the forum](https://www.google.com/search?q=site%3Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fen.sfml-dev.org) to prevent duplicates
- [X] I am here to report an issue and not to just ask a question or look for help (use the [forum](https://en.sfml-dev.org/forums/index.php#c3) or [Discord](https://discord.gg/nr4X7Fh) instead)

### Describe your issue here

I am creating a program with Qt 6.8 and SFML, I started off with SFML 2.6 and I decided to upgrade to SFML 3.0.
Migrating gave me no issues other than a new bug that involves `sf::Window::create(sf::WindowHandle Handle)`.
The program becomes unresponsive only when I use this specific overload.

This appears to only happen on the Windows build, as Linux doesn't experience this issue.

I found a forum post from 2016 that talks about the same issue that appears to have returned:
https://en.sfml-dev.org/forums/index.php?topic=21049.msg150558#msg150558

Sadly there are no error messages that I know of, the program just becomes unresponsive.

### Your Environment

- OS / distro / window manager: Windows 10
- SFML version: 3.0.0
- Compiler / toolchain: MingGW
- Special compiler / CMake flags: 


### Steps to reproduce

1. Start Program

```cpp
#include <QApplication>
#include <QWidget>
#include <QObject>
#include <QScopedPointer>

#include <SFML/Graphics.hpp>

class GameDisplay : public QWidget
{
    Q_OBJECT
public:
    explicit GameDisplay(QWidget *parent = nullptr, QString rom_url = QString()) : QWidget{parent},
                                                                                    render_window(new sf::RenderWindow(sf::VideoMode({800, 600}), "OpenGL", sf::Style::Default)),
                                                                                    texture({800, 600}),
                                                                                    sprite(texture),
                                                                                    m_initialized(false)
    {
        // Window attributes
        setAttribute(Qt::WA_PaintOnScreen);
        setAttribute(Qt::WA_OpaquePaintEvent);
        setAttribute(Qt::WA_NoSystemBackground);
        setAttribute(Qt::WA_DeleteOnClose);

        setWindowFlags(Qt::Window);
        resize(800, 600);
    };
    ~GameDisplay(){};

private:
    QScopedPointer<sf::RenderWindow> render_window;
    sf::Texture texture;
    sf::Sprite sprite;
    bool m_initialized;

protected:
    void showEvent(QShowEvent *event) override
    {
        // Initial initialization of the SFML widget
        if (!m_initialized)
        {

            render_window->create(sf::WindowHandle(winId())); // QWidget::winId() returns a native handle
            render_window->clear(sf::Color::Blue);
            render_window->draw(sprite);
            render_window->display();

        }
    };
    
    QPaintEngine *paintEngine() const override
    {
        return nullptr;
    };
};

#include "Main.moc" // Enable MOC for GameDisplay

int main(int argc, char **argv)
{
    QApplication a(argc, argv);

    GameDisplay w;
    w.show();

    return a.exec();
}
```


### Expected behavior

The program should respond and SFML's output should display within the confines of Qt's QWidget, which in this case is the GameDisplay class from the example

### Actual behavior

The program becomes unresponsive
